atient Health Questionnaire scores indicating depressive symptoms at screening. There were no differences in mean (SD) change in quality-adjusted life-years (screen, notify and treat, -0.06 [0.20]; screen and notify, -0.06 [0.20]; no screen, -0.06 [0.18]; P =.98) or cumulative mean (SD) depression-free days (screen, notify and treat, 343.1 [179.0] days; screen and notify, 351.3 [175.0] days; no screen, 339.0 [176.6] days; P =.63). Harms including death, bleeding, or sleep difficulties did not differ among groups. Conclusions and Relevance: In patients with ACS without a history of depression, systematic depression screening with or without providing depression treatment did not alter quality-adjusted life-years, depression-free days, or harms. Trial Registration: ClinicalTrials.gov identifier: NCT01993017.},
author = {Kronish, Ian M. and Moise, Nathalie and Cheung, Ying Kuen and Clarke, Gregory N. and Dolor, Rowena J. and Duer-Hefele, Joan and Margolis, Karen L. and {St Onge}, Tara and Parsons, Faith and Retuerto, Jessica and Thanataveerat, Anusorn and Davidson, Karina W.},
